{"Author": "BR from SF", "Date": "on December 21, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "way more once you introduce smart locks, thermostats", "Text": "Anyone who is interested in investing in the SmartThings ecosystem should be aware of the following:\n\n1. This \"hub\" is nothing but a set of antannae that sends/recieves information from your connected sensors/devices and forwards it on to the SmartThings cloud, where all the processing takes place. For example, say you wanted to turn on a light...so you open the SmartThings app on your phone, then press the button to turn the light on. Your phone forwards your command to the cloud where all of your devices are registered, then sends the 'on' command over the internet and down to your hub, which then broadcasts (via short range radio) the command to your device. The hub has zero functionality without the cloud whatsoever.\n\n2. The SmartThings cloud platform constantly has issues. Google \"SmartThings status\" to find their status page and look through the history of incidents. I count 30 between 1/1/18 and 4/20/18. If your just getting into SmartThings and suddenly your whole system stops working, how are you supposed to know that the cloud platform is broken and not your system? There's no documentation that tells you to go to the internet and check the platform status - you just automatically think your system broke and don't know why.\n\n3. Although this \"hub\" isn't too much money, realize that it is worthless without sensors and devices to connect with. SmartThings-branded sensors are fairly expensive and are really poorly made. Please read reviews of Samsung SmartThings Arrival Sensors, Motion Detectors, cameras etc. to get an idea of the cost and quality. Figure out for yourself what the total cost is for your particular needs. You could spend hundreds of dollars just on a few door/window sensors and a few motion detectors...way more once you introduce smart locks, thermostats, and light bulbs into your system. This reminds me of buying an ink jet printer for super cheap only to find the replacement ink cartridges costing an arm and leg.\n\n3. This is NOT a real home security system. Although there is a module in the SmartThings app called \"Smart Home Monitor\" that is what they are advertising as a security system, you must program the whole thing yourself with \"if this then do that\" type of rules. There is no out-of-the-box functionality for home security unless you buy the ADT version of the system. While simple rules can be setup using the SmartThings app, any situation that requires any type of complexity, like wait 30 seconds before setting off the alarm when a door is opened - will require you to login to the cloud and code your own routines using a Java-type language called \"Groovy.\" There is also a community-based rules engine project for the techno-savy. Even if you do just simply want an alarm to go off if a door or window is opened, YOU have to write the rules that make it happen, whether it's through the SmartThings app or using the cloud-based development environment. Of course you also have to buy a SmartThings compatible siren - - unless you just want to receive a text message when you're being burglarized.\n\n4. You don't need to - and probably shouldn't - buy SmartThings-branded sensors to work with this hub. As I said in point #1, this hub is just a pair of antanae that send/receive using the Zigbee and Z-wave protocols. These protocols are not proprietary to Samsung, so other manufacturers devices will work with this hub. You can download the SmartThings app and look in the \"Marketplace\" tab to see which devices have device handlers (drivers) that are available for this hub. For example, I would recommend Nest or Arlo cameras over the Samsung cameras, which actually, aren't even made by Samsung. I have door open/close sensors that cost half the price of SmartThings sensors and don't chew through batteries so quickly.\n\nI hope this information is helpful to anyone who is considering investing in a SmartThings system. Just keep in mind that things can get expensive really fast. I saw the hub on sale at BB and picked it up on a whim only to find it didn't do much without the add-ons. By the time I had bought the hub, 5 motion sensors, 7 door/window sensors, 2 cameras, a siren and a Phillips Hue starter kit, I had spent $1,200. Then of course you'll want to integrate it with Alexa or Google Home, so throw in a few hundred more for Echos in each room... then you'll want a compatible TV so you can change the channel with Alexa... anyways, it can become a money pit real fast.\n\nI'm giving this device 2 stars because once you spend enough $ to get all the things you'll expect from a home automation system, you'll wonder how you ever got along without it... but I'm a systems engineer and am comfortable dealing with technological challenges. Only 2 stars because this product really does seem to still be in beta testing, and I'm really bothered by how expensive the SmartThings-branded sensors/devices are given their pathetic quality."}
{"Author": "Francisco A.", "Date": "on December 20, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Will not work if your internet to cloud is down (no local control)", "Text": "Something that I did not like what the lack of local control (talk directly to other devices in your local network)... it always need to go to the cloud. Wink and Vera can work without connection to the cloud."}
{"Author": "Patt", "Date": "on December 20, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Bug makes this product useless.", "Text": "Really thought this would be a great addition to my smart home. I purchased this product mainly to pair with my Samsung smart TV, of which the model is listed as supported with this device. Upon receiving the item the hub never found the TV. I called Samsung's SmartThings support line and the operator confirmed that this was a bug with the firmware and that they were looking into a fix. It's been almost a month since that call and no update has been pushed to the device, nor has any update on a fix been relayed to me.\n\nI really want to like this product, but unfortunately it does absolutely nothing for me at the moment. I'm hoping Samsung fixes this issue, but I'm not holding my breath."}
{"Author": "Chris", "Date": "on December 20, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Best toy I ever bought.. very flexible for device support and reliable."}
{"Author": "rch7953", "Date": "on December 20, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "yeah this works pretty good. the phillips hue one crashes all the ...", "Text": "yeah this works pretty good. the phillips hue one crashes all the time. but sometimes my schlage locks get disconnected for no reason and it is a pain to get it back together. so that's why 4."}
{"Author": "Irvinfitz", "Date": "on December 20, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Nice but not nice.", "Text": "I was under the impression that this would control televisions and lights in the house. After further research, I found that this is a hub to connect other hubs or bridges to. So when I purchased WiFi lights, I had to purchase the bridge for the light to connect to the SmartThings hub. So much to learn and so many apps involved. There has to be a simpler way."}
{"Author": "Jody Windland", "Date": "on December 19, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "A must buy if you want a SMART HOME", "Text": "The setup was a bit confusing and was not working with my Schlage zwave door lock and the instructions were not the greatest on how to sync with my dimmer switch. I went to the Samsung site and they have a chat room for tech support. They took about 10 minutes to explain how to correctly set this up and it works so great. The customer support is superb. The instructions that come with the hub are horrendous. I give it five stars because I just love the hub, it works great, it comes with an app to control my door locks and light switches and their instant chat tech support is fully ready willing and able to help. LOVE IT."}
{"Author": "Loralulinda", "Date": "on December 19, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "It works well."}
{"Author": "Onepoorguy", "Date": "on December 19, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "great for home automation", "Text": "This device is great!! This allows you to automate various things in your home. You must purchase compatible items in addition to this to make it work. You also need a hardwire network outlet to plug into. This connects the hub to your home network (and therefore to your smartphone wherever you are in the world). The hub communicates with the automation devices wirelessly, so should be centrally located in your home.\n\nThis hub supports several different protocols. I have z-wave. I purchased z-wave outlets and switches, installed those, and then connected the hub using the smartphone app. In addition to being able to control lighting without having to walk to the switch, which can be very convenient when the switch for the floodlights is in the bedroom but you're outside and it's getting dark, but you can also program routines where it will turn lights on and off when you're not there to make it seem someone is there. Very useful if you're on vacation.\n\nA wide range of devices are available, including garage door openers and \"smart locks\". Personally I wouldn't want the ability to open my home remotely, but it does exist for those who do want it. I find controlling lights and the vacation lighting routines to be well worth the cost of this hub and the z-wave outlets and switches.\n\nIf you have a smart assistant, like the Google Home, you can link that to the hub also so that a simple voice command turns on lights. My favorite is to tell the assistant \"activate goodnight\" so that it will run the \"goodnight\" routine that turns everything off. No need to double-check before going to bed, just tell the assistant to run \"goodnight\"."}
{"Author": "Ahmed Mohammed", "Date": "on December 18, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "every one should have this thing!"}
{"Author": "MikeeDee1", "Date": "on December 18, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The hierarchy requires this hub", "Text": "This was our first hub and have had no regrets. It is required for our type of set up. We use Cree Bulbs and link them diectily to the SmartThings hub. We name all our bulbs acceodingn to there proximaty. After the first couple bulbs it became easier. Once they were set up in the smarthings app, I was able to bring them in to my Alexa to control them with voice. Please notice the hierarchy required for this smart house. There are wireless cameras that I will eventually connect. All our lighting is at our finger tips and controllable via voice as well through Alexa."}
{"Author": "WEZ_Indiana", "Date": "on December 18, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works great with ge z wave waal switch and monoprice z wave plug adapter"}
{"Author": "judy", "Date": "on December 18, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Smart Hub is so wonderful. Wish I would have purchased this hub first."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on December 18, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Seems like more of a toy than a serious product", "Text": "Seems like more of a toy than a serious product\nVery buggy, It keeps saying that switches are offline yet all my flows from stringify work fine. I can't control directly from smarttings though. All my addons work fine from other controllers, Smartthings recognized for weeks, but now will not register them. I'll replace this before i replace all of my switches, lights, thermostats and cameras."}
{"Author": "Joe", "Date": "on December 18, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Beware! Cannot control Samsung smart TV.", "Text": "Beware! Smartthings can not control Samsung TV any longer. Wasted purchase."}
{"Author": "Lenny", "Date": "on December 18, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "App is not intuitive to use, but at least it is functional. Hardware works well.", "Text": "I got this to act as a bridge between my existing Z-Wave network and Alexa. The hardware does what it's supposed to, most of the difficulty I encountered are from the app.\n\nWhen you first plug it in, and the tiny light is purple and flashing, that's because it is downloading and updating the firmware. Let it complete before trying to connect to it with the app. The app should have mentioned this, instead of saying it can't connect.\n\nWhen trying to add it to my Z-Wave network, I couldn't figure out where that option was. Turned out that you need to tap on the Hamburger button (3 horizontal lines, upper left corner), then tap on \"Hub is Online\" (it should be online, or you can't configure it). Then go to Z-Wave utilities and have it join an existing network.\n\nWhen I tried adding it to my master controller, my master controller showed that it had joined, but the app kept waiting. When I cancelled after a minute and tried to add again, it showed that it had already joined my network. It picked up nodes already in the network, but did not detect new additions to the network. I would probably need to have it leave and re-join the network to pick up the new devices.\n\nAfter that, adding the skill to Alexa and having it control my Z-Wave lights was easy."}
{"Author": "David J. Reed", "Date": "on December 17, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "Works ok, but some of the device setups are kind of clunky."}
{"Author": "steven nickerson", "Date": "on December 17, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great product and very simple to set up", "Text": "Great product and very simple to set up; The app isn't the best design but the Samsung community can walk you through almost any issue you have in linking various devices"}
{"Author": "Gene Forbes", "Date": "on December 17, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy to install and setup.", "Text": "This gadget works fine. I use it to control switches to my ceiling fan. Alexa interfaces with it perfectly."}
{"Author": "Jesse Smith", "Date": "on December 16, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "SmartThings admits it unreliable and they don't know how to fix it. You have to constantly reinstall your devices.", "Text": "Absolute garbage! I love the concept of being able to control all my lights with an app or adding the Alexa voice control with an Echo device, but the SmartThings Hub is garbage. It is constantly loosing the ability to control lights until you manually reset them, or uninstall/reinstall the lights in the hub software. When you look up the issue on the internet you find out that SmartThings admits this is a known issue and they don't know how to fix it. So every few days your stuff just doesn't work until you reset it. That's not a convenience, that's just more work because you bought a product that isn't reliable and the company who makes it just doesn't seem to care to fix it."}
{"Author": "zlajoie", "Date": "on December 15, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Mainly controlling the house lights and smart switches.", "Text": "Works well for my needs. Mainly controlling the house lights and smart switches."}
{"Author": "Anaguma", "Date": "on December 15, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I've checked it out a few times by dampening a sensor and it works fine. The sensor under the washing machine got dropped ...", "Text": "After the 3rd water problem in the house, I decided I needed an auto-water shutoff. The type shown on This Old House was exorbitantly expensive so I checked out EcoNet, Dome, and some other valves. It seems all the cheaper valves require a hub. Amazon had the SmartThings hub on sale for $49 so I just went with it and 4 water sensors at $30 each. This hub requires an ethernet cable and an open port on your router or wireless, but is not wireless itself. Plug it into the net, plug in the power, go online to the SmartThings site, set up an account, enter the code that came with the hub, and sit back and wait. I think it took about 15 minutes until it finally said that the hub was installed.\n\nAfter that, the water sensors were brought to about 10' from the hub and the battery activated. They appeared immediately on the app on your smartphone and there or on the Samsung site you name or rename the hubs. I got a Dome auto shutoff and it was a bit more problematic to link to the hub, but pushing the button on the valve 3x as fast as you can got it linked-3 times slowly didn't do it. The Dome valve is Z-Wave and the ST water sensors are Zigbee. With this hub you don't know the difference; your online account site will tell you which is which if you want to know with actual zigbee addresses or the ZWave device number shown in a table.\n\nI've checked it out a few times by dampening a sensor and it works fine. The sensor under the washing machine got dropped once so I moved it out a bit away from all the metal and it hasn't dropped since. The metal appliances must have been weakening the signal.\n\nI don't have any plans to use it for lights or doorbells and such. I already have the porch light and front hall light with motion sensors which work well enough.\n\nSo now, sitting in front of my black wireless router is a white ST hub. I haven't really touched it since I plugged it in."}
{"Author": "Justin B", "Date": "on December 15, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "works great with alexa and home automation"}
{"Author": "SK", "Date": "on December 14, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Three Stars", "Text": "Great idea, but need more time to get where this tech should be."}
{"Author": "GW", "Date": "on December 14, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy to setup", "Text": "Easy to setup. But, not secure."}
{"Author": "Ken", "Date": "on December 13, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Failed to bridge Samsung's own latest Smart TV with Alexa", "Text": "The only reason I purchased SmartThings was to enable Alexa to control my newly purchased Samsung TV. But no it doesn't work. The TV was detected in the SmartThings Andriod app and I can perform all the actions in it. But their Alexa skill failed to expose it to Alexa correctly. It shows up as a Switch device type in Alexa so nothing works. It's hard for me to believe Samsung cannot get it's own devices to work correctly because of an obvious software defect.\n\nThe 2nd problem is with Phillips Hue. I thought it can handle Hue bulbs directly since it support ZigBee. I was wrong. It still need Hue Bridge to connect to Hue bulbs."}
{"Author": "Don", "Date": "on December 12, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works well. No complaints.", "Text": "Works well. No complaints."}
{"Author": "James C. Liu", "Date": "on December 12, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Unreliable Connectivity", "Text": "Connectivity with Z-Wave devices are not reliable. Works with Leviton dimmers, Aertec sensor and the Linear Garage Door opener all the time, but the connection with Schlage door lock and GoControl light switches are not reliable at all."}
{"Author": "Leandro Alonso", "Date": "on December 11, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "nice product"}
{"Author": "Jimh615", "Date": "on December 10, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Rarely ever sounds an alarm if activated; it's dangerous.", "Text": "I have owned the Samsung SmartThings Hub and 6 sensors for over 2 years. Once installed I took for granted it was working; standing sentry over my safety. WRONG!!\nI am a 71 year old man who lives alone. My neighborhood is a high crime neighborhood with many home break-ins and many shipments stolen off of the front porch.\nI set up the Hub and positioned 6 sensors, 3 for door opening and 3 motion. I place a security door bar on my bedroom door at night.\nMY PLAN: If the Samsung security system detects either a door opening or a motion, an alarm will sound on my phone, giving me time to wake up, chamber a round, assume a defensive position on the side of the bed opposite the door and call 911.\nUnfortunately, in tests, conducted recently (me walking out into the sensored area, opening doors and walking under the motion sensors) the Samsung Hub security system rarely ever activated the loud siren notification sound on my phone, thus rendering the system useless. On the phone screen the sensors clearly show they are activating based on motion or a door opening\u2026.all of them work. But audio notification is not activated.\nFor this system to be effective an audible notification MUST activate. Whether you are traveling or out to dinner or whatever, the system must get your attention. But it doesn\u2019t. Rarely does it ever sound the audio notification.\nI am very disappointed and am looking for a different system.\n\nUpdate March 26, 2018:\n\nJust got back from a 10 day trip. I regularly check SmartThings on my Samsung S7 to insure no one has entered my house and caused a motion or intrusion alert. The system still does not notify me with an audible alert, even though I have spent hours and hours re-installing, re-booting etc. During this trip I noticed 2 of the sensors showed acceptable battery power, 86% but were listed now as UNAVAILABLE!!! When I cam home yesterday, I popped the battery out and then back in and went through the drill of reintroducing it to the system. Still no audible notification EXCEPT on ONE (1) of the 6 sensors, a motion sensor, it will on occasion send my phone an audbile notification when I walk under it, but not always.\n\nThe system is dangerous!!!! Because: You count on it alerting you if there is an intruder, and even though mine is a second generation it doesn't do that except now and then on only one of the 6 sensors. ALSO at random a sensor becomes 'UNAVAILABLE' while you're gone and you CANNOT reboot it remotely.\n\nFor a security system to be effective it must be reliable, always on alert, always ready to send you an audible signal that readily gets your attention. You must be able to sleep or enter your home/apartment with the confidence that your security system is on alert and prepared to notify you 24/7.\n\nThis system is dangerous and frustrating, so last night I threw it in the trash."}
{"Author": "David A. Davis", "Date": "on December 10, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great home automation system", "Text": "I love the SmartThings Home Hub. The Android app is intuitive and easy to use. The hub has worked flawlessly. I'm just gradually adding SmartThings to the hub. Prior to the SmartThings Home Hub, I tried an X10 system that was supposed to work over house wiring but was unreliable, often failed, which made it of not much use to me."}
{"Author": "RP", "Date": "on December 10, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love my Smart things", "Text": "Love my Smart things. I did need customer service for an issue with my door lock device. The customer service was amazing. I could not believe the time and effort that was spent with me. The representative spent about 30 minutes with me to resolve. It was refreshing to get this kind of service in this day and age. I am hooked on my smart things system. I keep adding more things to it. It also interfaces with the Echo products well."}
{"Author": "P. Santorello", "Date": "on December 9, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "NCC1701-ME", "Text": "I don't even know where to begin....I won't drone on about all the things you can do with it....I have no doubt you will do your research. All I can say is If you are a person who loves to tinker, tweak, and explore you should have gotten one yesterday. I get to play with hardware! I get to play with software! I get to integrate home improvement projects......all the while ever so slowly turning my house into the The ENTERPRISE.....and my wife doesn't suspect a thing...."}
{"Author": "Jason", "Date": "on December 9, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Smartthings is great", "Text": "I love Smartthings. I never had the V1 hub, but I haven't ever had an issue with the V2 hub going offline or not working in the several months since I first set it up. I did quite a bit of research and ultimately decided on Smartthings over Wink because of the expandibility and customization available, especially within the user community."}
{"Author": "Amy", "Date": "on December 8, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Absolutely love this hub", "Text": "Absolutely love this hub, it works really well with all kinds of products. I use GE z-wave switches, wemo switches, zigbee door and motion sensors, and a Logitech hub. All integrate seamlessly with the hub. It's really easy to set up all kinds of routines and automation tasks. As a developer I like that Samsung offers an API so you can plugin your own devices like a Raspberry Pi. Samsung does a great job keep things up to date with regular automatic firmware updates."}
{"Author": "Marcelo N. Alves", "Date": "on December 8, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works correctly but every firmware update I lose all devices ...", "Text": "Works correctly but every firmware update I lose all devices and have to configure it again. I opened a support case on Samsung for helping me figure out why this is happening."}
{"Author": "Yvonne Salazar", "Date": "on December 7, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Does not work offline and randomly removes itself from being online", "Text": "This is a fun toy to explore the opportunities of smart lighting. I bought two wemo WiFi plugs and a Samsung zig bee plug to see what can be done. Yes, you can turn everything on, everything off, or some other combination that suits your fancy. You can connect Alexa and use voice commands. All works well until you\u2019re disconnected to the internet. Then nothing works. Even if your local LAN is working, Smart Things won\u2019t work because it can\u2019t connect to cloud.\n\nSo, fun toy. Don\u2019t depend on it if you have unreliable internet service.\n\nTwo months after purchase, device went offline for a week despite attempts to reboot. Suddenly, it started working on its own. As stated before, it\u2019s a fun toy but not dependable.\n\nShortly after posting the previous paragraph - the account became inaccessible (a different problem from before). This seem to fix itself after a couple of hours. The lack of dependability is making this a less fun toy."}
{"Author": "Someone in Seattle", "Date": "on December 7, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Find out if you really need a hub for your devices if you have Alexa", "Text": "Easy to set up. Was told I needed a hub, even with Alexa. That turned out to be incorrect. It doesn't actually connect to much that I have - it is somewhat limited but hopefully more will be added to it. Alexa can connect to all my devices herself, so this is basically unneeded for me."}
{"Author": "Brian Reid", "Date": "on December 7, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Samsung SmartThings Hub", "Text": "Just starting out in home automation, I wasn't real sure of what I needed to do what. Having read the reviews of the SmartThings Home Hub and the very high recommendations I decided to grab this while on a Black Friday sale. As I said, I'm new to this so setup took a bit longer for me. I began with the the ST Hub, Hue Bulbs (with hub), Echo and Echo Dot. Getting this and the Echo to recognize the bulbs took a little more effort than I thought it would but it works amazing! I am able to recognize and control not only my bulbs but my satellite receiver and more. Just purchased the Harmony Hub and it worked almost out of the box. Make sure of a couple things first: Make sure that ALL of your Smart Home gadgets are on the same network, including the TV, Satellite, etc; use the app for Smart Things in order to get everything recognizable; if you are using Alexa, it will [usually] take a minute or two for things on your SmartThings to be recognized. Be patient and read the instructions. Overall, so far I highly recommend this for home automation. The further I go with automating everything, I may end up buying another!"}
{"Author": "CarlosECarlos", "Date": "on December 6, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "works well - needs to be on a ups"}
{"Author": "Amazon Queen", "Date": "on December 6, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I was very excited when I received my smart hub. The instructions were very lacking", "Text": "First, let me say I work in technology and have done so for many years. So I am not a newbie to technology. I was very excited when I received my smart hub. The instructions were very lacking. I had to google to find out where the welcome code was to be found. But, after getting all of the GE smart switches and dimmers installed, I set about including them on the hub. It all went really well. I connected everything to Alexa and\n\u201cShe\u201d saw them and was able to control them. If that had been the end of the story I would be giving 5 stars. However, after about 4 days of continuous operation the \u201csmart\u201d hub lost all of the devices. I have no idea why. When I went into the app it said there were no devices. I logged out of the app and back in, but no joy. I deleted the app and reinstalled, but again no joy. I reset the smart hub, excluded all devices (even though none were listed). I disabled the devices on Alexa and pulled out the air gap switch on all of the devices and tried reinstalling them. But the \u201csmart\u201d hub doesn\u2019t see them. This is a really expensive paper weight."}
{"Author": "Thai Duong", "Date": "on December 5, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Best smart hub!", "Text": "The best hub that you can buy right now for home automation. I use it with konnected which allows me to use my existing hardwire security system and integrate it with smartthings to monitor my home. Beats paying a monthly fee to a security company. Not as user friendly as Wink."}
{"Author": "stevenz59", "Date": "on December 5, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Disappionting", "Text": "Bought SmartThings hub to replace my vera lite. Had to put the vera lite back because the Smarthing Hub does not support adding / deleting codes for my Schalge lock. It can only open and close the lock. For my purposes, this is unacceptable."}
{"Author": "Jennifer Henderson", "Date": "on December 5, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great if you like constantly resetting sensors and the HUB", "Text": "I purchased this as my central home hub to work with all my Z-wave lights and locks, as well as pairing it with samsung multi sensors. It worked fantastic the first few weeks and now the multi sensors are constantly showing as unavailable. I had the siren paired with sensors and have set the alarm to away and had it never go off. The ring camera integration is worthless. Looks like I need to get all stuff together for a return and see if the Wink Hub works any better. Not happy with all the device errors and drop offs for something that I am using for smart home and security."}
{"Author": "Matt", "Date": "on December 5, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "Works and is simple to setup. Only down side is no WIFI"}
{"Author": "Whitney B", "Date": "on December 4, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "No Point in a hub", "Text": "If you ya e an iPhone with the HomeKit you don\u2019t need this. You can even use the app to control your locks on doors rather than buy ONE more thing to hook up to your inner webs"}
{"Author": "S. Lewis", "Date": "on December 3, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "One Star", "Text": "It is listed as a z-wave hub but it isn't compatible with Nortek, GoControl switches."}
{"Author": "ALoggins", "Date": "on December 3, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works as expected. Currently using it with Hue / ...", "Text": "Works as expected. Currently using it with Hue / Alexa / Echo and Samsung outlets for Xmas decorations."}
{"Author": "shawn gribble", "Date": "on December 3, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very disappointed.", "Text": "I purchased this as a recertified product from Amazon in January of this year and have not been able to use it at all. The product code that it shipped with did not work. I called Samsung and received a different code, it did not work either. Now I have this this setting around in my closet because I cant see myself just throwing it away. Very disappointed."}
{"Author": "jrzcell", "Date": "on December 3, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works will with Alexa", "Text": "When I first wanted to get it my wige was not impressed with the idea. Now that I have switches, plug modules and the door lock on the system she loves it. And the integration with Alexa is what makes it easy for her to use."}
{"Author": "cr", "Date": "on December 2, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "First Hub a Dud, Second is Fine", "Text": "The ST hub is reasonably versatile but management of the hub through the iPhone app is not intuitive. Also, the first hub I received had a very limited Z-wave range, less than 20 feet, so I ordered a replacement which has a good Z-wave range. The next problem was switching to the replacement hub required me to log into my ST account through my PC. I didn't know this initially, so it took a lot of searching and guessing to discover that I had an online ST account resulting from setting up the hub from the iPhone app. It then took a little more searching and guessing to figure out how to remove the first hub from my ST account, allowing the replacement to be added."}
{"Author": "George W", "Date": "on December 2, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Hate this thing.", "Text": "I hate this thing and do not recommend it.\nThe instructions are non-existent - just advertising blurb.\nBut the worst part is that to use the app I have to sign up and provide personal information. All I want to do is turn on a light bulb. There is no need to provide my birthdate to do that."}
{"Author": "GP", "Date": "on December 2, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "it works almost very good for everything", "Text": "it works almost very good for everything. it is a bit slow responisve sometimes because its mostly cloud based. its used every day for alot of devices in my home"}
{"Author": "Michigander in Oakland", "Date": "on December 1, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Spectacular product", "Text": "I'm crazy about my Smartthings Hub. I use it to automatically turn on lights, alert me (by phone) when someone rings the doorbell (when I'm not home) and alert me when I leave a door or window open when I leave the house. The Smartthings Hub is a bargain.\n\nI purchased mine in February 2017."}
{"Author": "jr", "Date": "on December 1, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Go with SmartThings Hub!", "Text": "I recently switched from Wink to SmartThings. I've had Wink for about 6 months now and my biggest complaint with Wink is that it is a closed system. Consequently, Wink supports a limited number of products. Wink's approach is to keep the user experience clean. Its noble, however it really limits the product. SmartThings is open, there are a ton of 3rd party supported products plus they support a ton more products in general. I did lose my NEST Thermostat capability with the SmartThings app, but I don't really need it. I've found that since I actually live in my home I'm not friggin' with the thermostat enough to bother.\n\nSmartThings is a better product. I've found the customization extremely useful and well done. It also actually (even though Wink walks you through the process nicely) has better at inclusion workflow. I like the way they leave the app in inclusion mode and you can walk around to your devices and get them connected. The automation is also better... I like the structure of the routines in SmartThings better than Robots in Wink. You can do more inside one routine and the UI is better in my opinion. The SmartThings unit itself is considerably smaller than Wink and feels a little cheaper (mechanically). SmartThings does add battery backup which is nice but you better have your network equipment on a UPS, if you don't then the batteries won't matter.\n\nI had a couple of switches that Wink always had problems maintaining a connection... this is not happening with the SmartThings hub, not sure why but its nice to have those switches back on-line."}
{"Author": "Anthony Kasongo", "Date": "on December 1, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good but could be better!", "Text": "Good product but need to extend devices list. Amazon is teaming up with other companies that make Alexa speakers like Fabiq that can't be added.\nYou should give people the ability to add not listed device on your catalog"}
{"Author": "Dave", "Date": "on November 30, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Beware: mandatory binding arbitration", "Text": "I was excited to get started with home automation. I unboxed the hub, plugged it into my network, installed the app, and then I saw it. Buried in the fine print of the terms of service is a mandatory binding arbitration agreement. In order to even set up the service, you must sign a contract in which you promise never to sue Samsung, no matter what, even if they break the law.\n\nI have to wonder why they feel compelled to preemptively strip consumer rights away. What are they trying to hide? Is the SmartThings Smart Home Hub so faulty that Samsung keeps getting sued? Is this service so bad that they have no choice but to make you promise never to sue even before signing up?\n\nI had no intention of suing, but the fact that they force you to give up that right before you even get started is very disturbing."}
{"Author": "Chris", "Date": "on November 29, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "After 2 years I'm still unimpressed", "Text": "After 2 years of owning this device I'm not impressed. I purchased this to use with my Alexa device along with monitoring doorways in my home.\n\nI'm honestly tired of asking 2 to 3 times to turn something off and on. I'm tired of having to constantly reconnect devices over and over again. After 2 years I'm tired. I didn't think I'd have to constantly be doing maintenance to get my lights to work. When one is utterly unresponsive to both the app and alexa I have to reboot the light and go through all the steps of adding it again.\n\nI'd say SmartThings devices work about 70% of the time as expected, but 70% is barely a C. When I'm ready to go to bed and ask the lights to be turned off I don't want to get up and troubleshoot.\n\nThings would be easier if there was a web interface, however there is only a phone app. The app is kind of clunky.\n\nIf I could do it all over again I wouldn't. I'm sure there are better products out there."}
{"Author": "Chris Cunningham", "Date": "on November 29, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "A must buy", "Text": "A must buy. I have about 10 thing connected to this. I would definitely recommend this device. if you want to start your smarthome this is the hub to start it with. it connects to just about all Zwave and Zigbee devices"}
{"Author": "Brian Andrew", "Date": "on November 29, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Died in 35 days so I can't return", "Text": "Unit dropped one of my light switches after the month return period was over refuses to add any more devices and refuses to remove existing devices would return if possible. Going to contact Samsung in the morning to do a warranty swap."}
{"Author": "Xhynk", "Date": "on November 28, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This thing is freaking amazing. Paired with our Echo Dot and having installed ...", "Text": "This thing is freaking amazing. Paired with our Echo Dot and having installed AskAlexa, WebCoRE, and a few other smart apps, this thing makes a WONDERFUL home automation device for entertainment and security. It definitely takes some setup to get it to do more than \"turn on light. send text when alarm system sensor opened\", etc. but I love love love tinkering with this kind of stuff. Very pleased so far."}
{"Author": "John Smith", "Date": "on November 28, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Doesn't support Verizon Samsung Galaxy S7. Useless.", "Text": "I have a Verizon Samsung Galaxy S7.\n\nAfter receiving the product, in trying to install the Smartthings Moble app to install it, I find that the app doesn't support my phone.\n\nUseless"}
{"Author": "ChattyMatty", "Date": "on November 28, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works great. Nice to connect the smart devices in our home."}
{"Author": "Carl S", "Date": "on November 28, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Lots of problems", "Text": "I have had a Smartthings hub, door sensors, and motion sensor for exactly one year. Not a day goes by that something does not work properly. It's a great idea - just doesn't work well. If you're the kind of person who likes coding and tinkering all of the time, it makes a neat project. If you're the kind of person who likes things to just work, I'd buy something else."}
{"Author": "Connoisseur", "Date": "on November 27, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Two Stars", "Text": "Terrible time connecting with some devices. No Windows interface."}
{"Author": "Reisler", "Date": "on November 27, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Well worth the learning curve.", "Text": "This is actually the second smart home hub that I tried. I like the SmartThings hub because it doesn't care how many diverse owners of devices in a household you might have. You have no limitations to functionality as to what account is what or who is using a device or service. In a large home with a fairly large multi generation family who all have their own tech devices, this hub really shines. It has a huge number of compatible devices and larger still if one is willing to learn how to use device handlers and work with this hub. We use seven Echo Dots (so far) for voice automation, lists, games for the grandkids, and a Hue bridge for lights. I\u2019m looking at Harmony hubs to handle our own entertainment systems because we buy our own content. The single lesson I have learned since starting down the smart home path, is that no one device does it all well. You\u2019re going to wind up with a neat little row of devices next to your router and in my opinion, the SmartThings hub is critical for the basics like motion, temperature, video and security. This hub is a very good starting point."}
{"Author": "Rob", "Date": "on November 27, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This is the best thing for people who want smart home and home ...", "Text": "This is the best thing for people who want smart home and home automation but don't want to learn how to set it up themselves directly between smart home things. I got mine for $50 on sale and I've added so many things:\n\n10+ contact sensors\n5+ water sensors\n6 smoke sensors\nLight bulbs (from hue and smartthings)\nOutlets and switches from Wemo and Kasa (3rd party device handler needed)\nThermostats (nest with 3rd party device handler)\nSchlage locks\nSiren\nMotion sensor\nIris keypads (3rd part device handler needed)\nAnd soon I'll be adding some 3rd generation august pro locks that will also integrate\n\nThis also integrates with IFTTT for things that don't interoperate with smartthings."}
{"Author": "Clubbby", "Date": "on November 26, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy to setup and configure", "Text": "Easy to setup and configure. App is pretty intuitive. Works consistently. Range seems pretty good. I have a smaller home, but everything is in it's range."}
{"Author": "Tech Girl", "Date": "on November 26, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Difficult Setup", "Text": "I have had a very difficult time with this product, so much so, that I have decided to return it. I currently have a Wink hub which was a very easy setup. I decided to upgrade since a lot of the new Smart Home products now require the Wink Hub 2. When I looked at the reviews of this product versus the Wink Hub 2, this one looked like it would be a better product, plus I love Samsung products.\n\nI have several smart home products such as the Amazon echo, lights, switches, garage door open and schlage locks. This Samsung Smart Home hub recognized none of them. To setup the locks I followed the instructions to put in the programming code, etc. all of which worked fine with the Wink hub. I could not get any of the locks to connect to the Samsung hub. So disappointed. I spent several hours on this so I am going to return it at this point. Such a bummer."}
{"Author": "PLT", "Date": "on November 26, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "5-star", "Text": "We love our hub!"}
{"Author": "Mark Moeglein", "Date": "on November 25, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Effective controller... just be prepared to be patient!", "Text": "While it is infuriatingly early in the SmartHome revolution, this is the best hub that I could identify. I like that it is becoming more and more cost-effective. I think that will only improve the uptake, and we will see these popping up more and more."}
{"Author": "Jenny S.", "Date": "on November 24, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not worth the head ache", "Text": "The Smart Things hub was a high let down, in my particular case the hub was very slow to exictue commands or just did not do the commands at all. Even with the other devices in the Things Lineup the individual apps, for the devices, worked far better and faster then the ST app and the ST app also limited the features or it's own devices."}
{"Author": "Kenneth L. Foster", "Date": "on November 23, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Home Security!!!", "Text": "Great Product, works great."}
{"Author": "Frank", "Date": "on November 22, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "The best hub out there... Keep it up..."}
{"Author": "Thomas Hafemann", "Date": "on November 22, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "not worth it", "Text": "what a waste of money. I spent 2 hours trying to connect things. Alexa connection was a pain. Then once it connected there wasn't much I could do. my 2 year old tv's don't connect. none of my cameras, weather stations, appliances, thermostats, etc don't work with it. unless one purchases the very specific devices, nothing will connect. it seems that there isnt a standard code that is shared across devices. in order to connect everything i am going to have to upgrade most everything and purchase the very vendor specific smarthome connection devices. if I go down that path, I expect to have 7 or 8 completely separate hubs. I would have thought samsung would have their act together. nope! they have separate products with separate connection accounts for their smarthome products. indtructuons were vague and unclear. even going to their get started web site it took a bit of digging to figure out where to find the code. what a waste of time and money."}
{"Author": "Jennifer", "Date": "on November 21, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This Family Loves SmartThings!", "Text": "Love this product with Alexa and Google Home. We have a number of lights bulbs, switches, smart plugs, motion sensors, and 2 locks connected to it. We setup Routines and Scenes to help with getting the kids to bed and up in the morning. For example, we created a SmartThings Routines for bedtime to turn down the lights in the livingroom and play room and tge lights to a certain brightness in the bedrooms. Also, we created a ST Routine to lock bith doors, turn off the lights, and set the thermostat to 68 degrees. We also setup water leak sensors and motion sensors in the basement so we know if a pipe bursts or to turn on the lights in the basement as soon as we open the door to avoid falling diwn the stairs. Lastly, we also created a vacation mode, so the our lights come on at different times and in different rooms when we're away. We have cameras setup too, but use Nest for that."}
{"Author": "H", "Date": "on November 21, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Simple setup, no issues after a few months, lights and sensors worked seamlessly."}
{"Author": "Louis A. Rinaldi Jr.", "Date": "on November 21, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Terrific Product.", "Text": "Works great, so easy to work."}
{"Author": "NewBee", "Date": "on November 21, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I love this hub", "Text": "I love this hub.\nConnected over 20 devices.\nSaved me ton of money just replacing home monitoring services.\nThere are over 1k devices compatible with this hub.\nPlus if you get google home, you can control most with voice commend.\nOr just use any android phone for voice commend."}
{"Author": "AlexK", "Date": "on November 21, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Garbage", "Text": "Flaky cheap device that failed to connect and setup correctly. Returned and replaced for a wink hub 2 that worked fine."}
{"Author": "Kim Sun Jin", "Date": "on November 20, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "It is a good product"}
{"Author": "Chris", "Date": "on November 20, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "So much room for improvement", "Text": "I like it, but Samnsung is not utilizing even half of it's potential. There is so much more Samsung could do. For starters they could activate the Bluetooth radio that is already installed on all units. The software is NOT immediately intuitive, and there is no real support from Samsung. To get the device to behave like I want, I have to write special programs with CoRE (look it up, it is what Samsung should have natively)."}
{"Author": "Michael Jones", "Date": "on November 20, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This makes it annoying if you try to use any scheduling tasks", "Text": "Works very well to integrate my Ecobee thermostat and z-wave devices. I can't seem to get it to set to the correct time (I think it is stuck on GMT but the time zone is set correctly. This makes it annoying if you try to use any scheduling tasks."}
{"Author": "Carlton Cabral", "Date": "on November 18, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works ok so far. I need to mess with it some more to get it to our liking's."}
{"Author": "Hunter Witt", "Date": "on November 18, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Proprietary browser required to make an account to use it", "Text": "Companies need to stop making new web browsers. Proprietary browser to make an account to use your product? I have Chrome, and that doesn't work as stated. No wonder this is on sale for half off."}
{"Author": "Chris Z", "Date": "on November 18, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Look Elsewhere", "Text": "This thing works about 5% of the tine. I've had it for at least a year, it has seen provably 30 firmware updates and still cant lock or unlock my door. Worked for a week, then decides to work once every 20x. Find another smart hub."}
{"Author": "Mike Ferris", "Date": "on November 17, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I became tired of having to play nursemaid to it.", "Text": "I guess these are Ok for sum but I became tired of having to play nursemaid to it. Things work then don't work. Each time a new firmware update occurred things would drop out and had to be reloaded. I eventually sold it to someone with more patience."}
{"Author": "marco", "Date": "on November 16, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Is better Wink", "Text": "Its better wink"}
{"Author": "myself", "Date": "on November 16, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "but I ultimately found it fairly easy to accomplish", "Text": "It took a bit of reading to be certain I understood how to implement the Hub properly, but I ultimately found it fairly easy to accomplish. So far, I've installed 10 ea. Schlage Connect locks on my exterior doors, and a Sonos Connect streaming device. I've also set up an Amazon Echo Dot, so I can use voice control with all of the devices. Having added a virtual switch that I set up in IDE, I can also use the Echo to lock the doors. It's worth noting that Echo does not allow setting up locks directly, for security reasons. Therefore, I followed their lead and set up locking only, forgoing the use of voice control for unlocking. Also, for the Schlage locks, I can heartily recommend Rboy Apps for SmartThings, as their Door Lock App and Universal Lock Device Handler have made setting up the locks, including adding and deleting codes, much easier.\n\nAt this point, everything is working very well, with all devices reacting properly and reporting their status almost immediately when commands are sent."}
{"Author": "Amparo", "Date": "on November 16, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works perfectly but the advance features are not user friendly.", "Text": "Works perfectly but for some devices and advanced features it requires some investigation and publishing your own smart apps (most of the times you only need to copy the code that someone else did or sells)."}
{"Author": "Tim Schreyack", "Date": "on November 16, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "No support for setting brightness or colors in scenes and routines", "Text": "Scenes and routines do not support setting brightness level or colors for devices. Isn't that one of the most basic features of lighting control??? I'm still in shock this is not a feature."}
{"Author": "Oscar Drum", "Date": "on November 16, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Two Stars", "Text": "It works but it's not reliable."}
{"Author": "Father Lucifer", "Date": "on November 15, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Will not pair with devices", "Text": "Tried all night to get this hub to work with my builbs and switches. Not one of my devices were found. Wen't to the Samsung Forum for smartthings hub and read there were many of these units that were released defective. I'll stick with my Echo Plus with internal hub, Seems to be working fine for me."}
{"Author": "Jeff", "Date": "on November 15, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "Great product."}
{"Author": "Yuri Dogandjiev", "Date": "on November 15, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "... are already on the right track to building your perfect smart home", "Text": "If you are reading this review then you are already on the right track to building your perfect smart home. At this point in time the SmartThings hub has at least three huge advantages over its competitors:\n1. It has a great out of box experience where it works with a large set of tightly integrated devices with minimal setup involved typically just involving wizard flows. This includes all of the SmartThings branded accessories as well as pretty much anything on this page - https://www.smartthings.com/products.\n2. It has an amazingly active community of users and developers who build custom Device Handlers and SmartApps to greatly extend the functionality and compatibility of the SmartThings hub. Because of that, the SmartThings hub can stitch together your disparate ZigBee, Z-Wave, and Wi-Fi based devices (e.g. like the ones from TP-Link and WeMo) into a single point of control and automation.\n3. It has the support of a large company that is unlikely to go bankrupt or give up on smart home automation anytime soon. if anything, Samsung is continuing to heavily invest in smart home automation and I believe standards like ZigBee and Z-Wave have reached a sufficient level of maturity that most smart home components bought today will last for at least another decade of iterative hub controllers and compatible accessories.\n\nOverall, I love my SmartThings hub and it has truly become the center of my smart home. My only advice to you - try to purchase Z-Wave or ZigBee (in that order) devices for your home when possible. Wi-Fi based switches and other accessories from companies like TP-Link, WeMo, etc.\nmight occasionally have a shiny feature that your really like or attract you with their \"hub-less\" advertisements but they will always be dependent on the whims of network quality, unstable services, unsupported device handlers, etc. Nothing beats local execution when it comes to creating a fast and reliable smart home."}
{"Author": "PattyCO", "Date": "on November 14, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Requires Samsung to know your daily schedule", "Text": "I suppose this would be OK if it didn't REQUIRE internet access. Meaning, if the internet is down, so is this. Plus, I couldn't bring myself to trust a company that has so many problems to maintain (and possibly sell??) information on when I'm home and when I'm away and what my daily habits are. I returned this and bought a VeraPlus which works without a connection to the internet (requires internet access only if you want cell phone access)."}
{"Author": "SF Amazon Fan", "Date": "on November 14, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Unreliable. Works maybe 25% of the time", "Text": "Works maybe 25% of the time. Constantly loses connectivity. Avoid, not ready for primetime"}
{"Author": "JPP", "Date": "on November 14, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Constantly offline and having to reinstall", "Text": "Everytime I\ufe0f pair a switch the app says offline despite the hub having a green line. I\ufe0f have to reset and reinstall the hub. Returning this"}
{"Author": "Mystery", "Date": "on November 14, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Dumb things DOA", "Text": "This dumb thing arrive DOA. Not happy. I will get a replacement and hope for better luck next time. FYI wait until it goes on sale for $50 new which it does occasionally."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on November 14, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great to control my Schlage lock through \"rboyapps\"", "Text": "I use this primarily to control my lights, Schlage Connect lock and sprinklers. The hub works well and once you are familiar with how to create some of the automation triggers, it is pretty user friendly. Beware that the hub does not connect to everything (Wave and Zigbee only) unless you do some customization. Before buying, take a look at all the different things you ar looking to install, if not you may be disappointed. The SmartThings Community is pretty cool though. For example I purchased a customized app to control my Schlage Lock through \"rboyapps\" and it gives me a great deal of flexibility."}
{"Author": "Katie", "Date": "on November 14, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very convenient.... when the app / ...", "Text": "Very convenient.... when the app / lights work, that is. Very temperamental- no rhyme or reason why it chooses to work one time and not another. We\u2019ve trouble-shot the WiFi, connections, phone service, weather, wind conditions... you get the point..."}
{"Author": "chris hansen", "Date": "on November 13, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great product", "Text": "Works great with google and my switches"}
{"Author": "MRMAZ2510", "Date": "on November 13, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works flawlessly if you pay ATTENTION!", "Text": "I have used this right out of the box to hook up locks, lights, Alexa, switches for lights and lamps and have never had one down day or an ounce of problems with this hub, v2. It works as I expected, you just have to be sure that you buy what is compatible, like Z-wave, or if you already have a bunch of switches and hubs just go to smartthings.com to see what is compatible. You don't have to be an electrician or write code to buy this hub and connect all of the things you want. If you are replacing existing light switches you just need to cut power and attach the wires exactly like they were on the existing one. I am handy around the house so none of this was hard at all.\n\nWorks great and no downtime = happy guy! \ud83d\ude01"}
{"Author": "Mase Hacker", "Date": "on November 13, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "works great easy to use and the app is great", "Text": "works great easy to use and the app is great.\nthey do need more documentation on how to setup and use the device handlers and hardware handlers on their website."}
{"Author": "Wood", "Date": "on November 13, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Bought new, given used", "Text": "Bought new, opened to see already used and unique code \u201cinvalid\u201d\n\nNeedless to say, waste of time"}
{"Author": "David Reed", "Date": "on November 12, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not a good start to setting up a smart home system", "Text": "We had this product for around 30 days. It deleted itself twice. Luckily we only had 10 devices linked, but what a hassle to have to disassociate and reset each item after the hub deletes itself. Not a good start to setting up a smart home system. Tech support tells me that it looks like the \"end user\" deleted the device, however I am 100% certain that we did not. We have monitored security separate from the hub, but do not have time to keep troubleshooting this device for simple tasks like lighting. We chose Smartthings based on reviews, and really wanted to like this product. Looks like it isn't going to work for us. I never write reviews but wanted others to be aware. It may work great for you since I saw very few bad reviews. This was just our experience."}
{"Author": "Dan", "Date": "on November 11, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very good when using z-wave", "Text": "This purchase was worth it for me. There are a few limitations in processes (like you can't easily alert multiple people of an alarm without doing a work-around) but the overall setup is pretty logical. I use most z-wave plus devices and once the closer modules started the signal has been able to communicate to the furthest ones through other modules. This is a good purchase if you are getting into home security and/or automation because ti works with every one of the devices I have purchased so far."}
{"Author": "DGK", "Date": "on November 11, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Worse than the Home Connect, terrible App, questionable wireless reception", "Text": "I bought this as an experiment in home automation for late 2017, specifically comparing it wink hub 2 (2016 release) and the home connect (also returned). I ended up returning it for a number of reasons.\n\nSmartThings was aquired by Samsung, who has taken the standalone hub and started down the path of uniting it with a mesh router. The Home Connect (or pro). Unfortunately, the Home Connect is a terrible router and a worse mesh router. There are serious latency issues that appear every minute or so, creating lag on voice calls that makes it untenable. The Home Connect Pro is significantly slower and less perform at than the 2011 Apple AirPort Extreme. That is a fact. Coupled with this are features that are either broken or buggy (parental control for example). So why mention the Connect Home products? Because as a SmartThings hub, they actually work quite well. I had no issues with lag or reception on any of the wireless in wall dimmers or motion sensors around the house (z wave). However as a WiFi system these had to go...\n\nSo I resolved to try the older SmartThings hub (this product). And...\n\nReception\n\nReception suddenly became an issue. Same devices, same locations for everything, including the hub and... dimmers no longer working. I purchased a plug to extend the z wave and...still not much joy. Mostly it works, but then occasionally the status is not received or the switch fails to function. If something isn\u2019t reliable then it is defective.\n\nThe app\n\nI\u2019m used to great apps and a perfect user interface. I\u2019m an iPhone user and I expect perfection in these areas. Do a search for SmartThings and you\u2019ll see a 2 or 2.5 star rating for the latest version. I found the app to be difficult to navigate and overly complicated, specifically compared to the wink app which is much MUCH better, cleaner and more professional on every level. Beyond that, inconsistent and slow status updates and a clunky overall feel, with areas that seem like duplicates and bizarre buttons all over the place. Yes it works, but it is clearly not well designed. I frankly don\u2019t understand how Samsung could release such a product, unless this is the norm.\n\nSo, this has gone back to amazon and I am sticking with the wink hub which is leaps and bounds better. Beyond that, I have also moved to Lutron Caseta dimmers as they work flawlessly and are much less cheap feeling than the leviton z wave dimmers (rebranded ge/jasco is my guess). Caseta Connect directly to the wink hub.\n\nAnother major issue is lack of WiFi on the smartthings hub. We all know that WiFi routers can\u2019t often be placed perfectly. For other wireless devices like z wave etc... the placement of the hub is critical. Higher and more central is better. Who has a cable in the center of their house? Second floor? Unlikely. The wink hub can be placed anywhere and so far has functioned flawlessly.\n\nSorry Samsung, but this product is outdated and outclassed. You\u2019ve been warned."}
{"Author": "TS", "Date": "on November 10, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Smart Toys", "Text": "It is a toy, new sensors are out of range - strange is that sensors closer to unit are randomly out of range versus sensors installed farther from unit are up and running. I tested two different control units in different locations and see similar weaknesses.The solution is Vera which has more difficult configuration but when everything is paired works very well and most importantly it is very stable. Schlage locks have more options when units are connected to Vera than Smart Toys - both out of the box. Smart Toys have better, nice looking app for smart phone versus vera but in long run functionality is much better for vera products."}
{"Author": "Emer", "Date": "on November 10, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "One Star", "Text": "Complete crap - never worked"}
{"Author": "Tek", "Date": "on November 10, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Unstable, not reliable, unworthy! Buy a different one.", "Text": "For a Samsung, I\u2019m really disappointed in this device. It constantly loses connection to the web, even tho the light says it is running normally. When it does this, you lose the ability to control items remotely, but more importantly, it fails to execute the schedules and automations programmed. That tells me the programs do not reside in the device, but rather it takes external ques from the web for the no-frills scheduled activities. That seems like a huge oversight and a lot of excess communication and insecurity. Also, why does it have battery backup built-in, when it can\u2019t handle simple operations without an internet connection? After 6 months of having to constantly reset the device, and multiple instances of things not happening like they should, I am getting rid of this and getting a different brand.\n\nNote also, this device DOES NOT integrate with Samsung smart TVs, this is a well-known problem and Samsung has not offered any firmware updates to fix it. It also has a very hard time keeping connect with Bose SoundTouch devices."}
{"Author": "Jessica", "Date": "on November 10, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Does not fully automate Lightify Smart Bulbs", "Text": "I purchased this centrally control all of my smart devices. One of the primary devices I have are 6 Lightify Connected Smart Bulbs. It will not let me set a rule that adjusts light intensity AND color, i.e. soft white-cool white-daylight, etc. Therefore, this cannot centrally automate all of my devices."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on November 10, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Hub works flawlessly. Now have control of lights with ...", "Text": "Hub works flawlessly. Now have control of lights with my Echo's and SmartThings App with more to come. However, I paid way to much to find out less than 3 days later that it's half price."}
{"Author": "M. Chandler", "Date": "on November 9, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "SmartThings and RBoyApps is a winning combination!", "Text": "So this review is more about a third party app that works with Samsung SmartThings. I was coming from the Wink Smart hub and moved over to SmartThings when wink was purchased by i.am - his products just seem to go downhill.\n\nSo a bit about my setup - I have a few Schlage locks ( Schlage Z-Wave Connect Camelot Touchscreen Deadbolt with Built-In Alarm, Works with Amazon Alexa via SmartThings, Wink or Iris, Satin Nickel, BE469 CAM 619 ) and a few Blink security cameras ( Blink Home Security Camera System for Your Smartphone with Motion Detection, HD Video, 2 Year Battery and Cloud Storage Included - 3 Camera Kit ) . I was surprised and really disappointed that SmartThings and Schlage didn't have anything built in.\n\nThen came rboyapps to the rescue. It just so happened that the 2 things I really like (my locks and camera), rboyapps makes custom device handlers and Smart apps that integrate seamlessly. I'll say that I know nothing about programming this stuff or what a device handler is or anything like that, but their site has step by step instructions. Basically you go to your Samsung account, copy and paste a few things and then it shows up in your apps. I will say that I thought about purchasing the products for a week or so because its a few dollars, but I just couldn't find anything as good and after a while was thinking something like \"I've spent 20 or 30 bucks on much dumber things - like a fake horse skeleton for halloween, but I digress, haha\".\n\nAnyway, back to the app...The apps they have created lets you remotely change codes, unlock lock, set expiring times, perform all kinds of cool actions when the lock is locked/unlocked for the lock.\n\nWith the Blink Camera smart app, I believe (like 99% sure) they worked directly with the Blink company and create some cool software to integrate DIRECTLY with your blink cameras. Arming/Disarming, watching the cameras, changing settings, etc (again - all from within smartThings).\n\nSo what I had programmed with their software was that when me or my wife locked the Schlage lock from the keypad, it would automatically ARM the blink cameras. Really cool feature, but what I found out was that after we would lock the lock and the blink cameras would ARM, we didn't have enough time to get out of the garage with the car where one of the cameras were - I wanted to have a delay between the locking of the lock and the arming of the blink camera. So....\n\nI contacted them with their support email asking them about the feature or a way it could be done. Maddie responded within 10 minutes walking me through a couple other questions I had and then indicated that it was not possible but would mark it as a future feature for the developers. That was 2 days ago.\n\nMaddie sent me an email today indicating that this new feature is now in the smart app and all I had to do was follow the step by step instructions for an update. It works flawlessly and me and my wife are really excited. More so me, because I set all this stuff up and she was getting annoyed with all the technology, but she is really coming around.\n\nSo now, we can lock the Schlage lock, have the lock app automatically wait a number of minutes I tell it to and then arm the blink cameras. Gives us enough time to get out of the garage.\n\nI know I may sound like a paid shill or whatever and they didn't give me any discounts or any free stuff. I paid full price for the software, but their team works really hard and is super responsive, and I really appreciate that, I guess you get what you pay for.\n\nIf you have blink cameras or schlage locks, or both (like me), don't spend hours upon hours searching for something awesome and free - it doesn't exist - I tried. I don't work for them, but if you have any questions about my setup with or without their stuff, I can answer.\n\nThanks,\nMatt"}
{"Author": "Eusbeio Saenz", "Date": "on November 9, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works great. The house has integrated perfectly"}
{"Author": "Alan Fischer", "Date": "on November 9, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Simple and Smart", "Text": "Works Great, Easy Set-up, Ultimate Convenience"}
{"Author": "David C", "Date": "on November 8, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "meh", "Text": "I don't have the time to go through all the problems we have with this thing. Sadly its the most universal smart home controller on the market without going professional. Too bad you cant group lights together. Try adjusting the light level in a large room 1 bulb at a time!"}
{"Author": "Jay Madhu", "Date": "on November 7, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "not the new Samsung Smart Things hub", "Text": "Does not have full functionality with Schlage Connect locks, despite what the Schlage website claims. Will lock and unlock, but cannot remotely setup or delete user codes. As per Schlage customer service, Wink hubs and a few others WILL work, not the new Samsung Smart Things hub. Very disappointing as am a big Samsung supporter."}
{"Author": "Larry Brown", "Date": "on November 7, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "SmartThings for the win!", "Text": "SmartThings hub (v2) is working great and is reliable. Great compatibility with most devices.\n\nAdding webCoRE REALLY improves the end user's ability to program just about what ever you want without having to find that perfect specific app.\n\nAdditionally, I use some of the RBoy apps and device handlers for my Honeywell Z-Wave thermostat and Linear Garage Door controller. RBoy is definitely worth the money and they have good active support as the SmartThings platform evolves!"}
{"Author": "Dirk Gaudeus", "Date": "on November 6, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "worked fine. Nice thing to use", "Text": "Arrived quickly. For use in Europe, needed a connector for the electricity, but when installed, worked fine. Nice thing to use, was bought to collaborate with Google Home and works fine. Nice thing, this SmartThings hub."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on November 6, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "good, not great", "Text": "In general, I am satisfied with this as a replacement for my legacy X-10 home automation system. X-10 with ActiveHome Pro offers a greater level of configuration than this product (i.e. \"security\" mode - random on/off times around a defined schedule), but Z-wave has been more reliable and offers much more in the line of available devices. Oh, and then there's internet connectivity, which has helped me to solve other issues.\n\nI purchased this device in March 2017 and have owned it for 8 months now. I have not had any bad experiences with firmware updates as I read in reviews before I purchased. Samsung has notified users in advance (by email) of updates."}
{"Author": "David R. Hilgendorf", "Date": "on November 6, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This thing is useless without Z-Wave or Zigbee devices", "Text": "This thing is useless without Z-Wave or Zigbee devices. I have it installed (bought it half off here), but not much use for it until I rewire my entire house with expensive devices and switches. Expect to invest hundreds, if not thousands of dollars to make your home \"smart.\""}
{"Author": "bej", "Date": "on November 5, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "What a joke.", "Text": "Samsung has really dropped the ball on this garbage. You'd think they'd take the whole smart home thing more seriously and see it as an investment into the future for consumer electronics. All my connected lights will randomly turn off at once. Nothing is in the event log, it just happens. Samsung can't come up with an answer. I've had to resort to keeping the hub unplugged...so I have a $100 ugly little box sitting there doing nothing. The smartphone app is horrible as well.Try contacting Samsung for help, that's a laugh."}
{"Author": "Robert", "Date": "on November 4, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works great for basic home automation", "Text": "I got this for my wife for her birthday. She is a gadget person, but until I started hooking up a few things to it she really didn't 'get it'. I got the front porch, entry hallway lights on and then she really got into it. Now we have the Kitchen, master bedroom, and dining room setup on it. Alexa is also setup. I got a motion sensor and have some basic automation setup.\n\nWe use Alexa and our SmartPhones to interact.\n\nFor some moderately advanced features you do need to sign into the website online (I had to add a couple of device handlers to do some stuff I wanted to do).\n\nOverall she is happy and really getting into it. I got it while it was on sale for $49 in September 2017.\n\nWorks with Z-wave devices. I have an Android App and use Alexa. It does require internet connectivity, so it your internet goes down, you loose any automation."}
{"Author": "Red", "Date": "on November 4, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good hub, an inexpensive way to start automatic your house", "Text": "Very happy with it and easy to set up. It works perfect with Alexa Echo dot. It been very easy to integrate the light switches and the front lock"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on November 3, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Can't recommend - more hassle than it is worth.", "Text": "Can't recommend \u2013 more hassle than it is worth.\n\nThe good \u2013 it interfaces with my Google Home in a simple and clear way. I say \u201cOK Google turn off the living room light\u201d and when the device actually works, the light goes off. My son has one and it works flawlessly for him but he has just a couple of switches connected to it.\n\nThe bad \u2013 I have 25 wall switches and a Google Home connected. I bought it in December of 2016 because my VeraPlus hub did not support the Google Home. Once every few days the SmartThings hub reports one of my switches as \u201cunavailable\u201d. That should be a simple process of reconnecting it but generally it takes about an hour to stand at the switch put it in paring mode and have it ignore it. A couple of reboots of the hub and a couple of pairing attempts the SmartThings interface will tell you it failed but the device will actually show up in the list of devices. The device will have to be renamed and then any programs that were associated with the switch will have to be reprogrammed. This has happened dozens of times.\n\nThe fix was apparently do a network repair, which is a utility that comes with SmartThings. It ran for 14 hours before I killed it. No z-wave network can be that broken \u2013 or can it?\n\nThey have convenience programs that help you do certain things. I tried one of them that will turn on or off several switches when you double tap one of them. I set it up to turn all the switches off in the master bathroom when I double tapped off the main bathroom light. It sort of worked but it also turned them all off randomly. Sometimes it turned them all off when you did a single tap. Sometimes it turned them all off when you turned off some other light. Once it turned them all on for no apparent reason.\n\nNot worth the hours I spent over the past year keeping my z-wave network running on the SmartThings when my VeraPlus works perfectly."}
{"Author": "Hamza", "Date": "on November 3, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "MUST HAVE FOR SMARTHOME", "Text": "If you want to start the smart home game this a must it compatible with any z wave product and it great product"}
{"Author": "Marvin Lipschitz", "Date": "on November 3, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Much easier than Insteon and more reliable.", "Text": "Much easier than Insteon and more reliable."}
{"Author": "Stuart Woodward", "Date": "on November 2, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "It is absolutely useless.", "Text": "I suspected that it would not work with many of the cameras and devices that I already had, but I found that it was not capable of working with anything. It works with a handful of cameras, but not the ones that I have. It is supposed to work with zwave devices. I have tried it with a number of different wvave switches and thermostats that I have and found that it didn't work with any of them. It is absolutely useless."}
{"Author": "Donatello", "Date": "on November 2, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Need to be tech savvy to get full potential of thsi", "Text": "It's a good hub, but if you really want to reach it's full potential, you need tech knowledge. I went in hoping this would be the central location to access all my smart enabled devices, but there are limitations. Craftmsan garage door opener is no longer supported, for the Ring doorbell, you can only view the battery status, although motion notifications can be set, they are very delayed. Also, you can't view live video or respond to a doorbell from the ST app, you have to use the native Ring app. The work arounds for all this either require you to code apps or find one that someone has done and load it, which I haven't taken the time to figure out yet.\n\nI haven't changed out anything related to lighting or added security to my home yet, but I guess when I do that, this will be more useful."}
{"Author": "Adam", "Date": "on November 2, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The SmartThings hub does everything I thought it would. ...", "Text": "The SmartThings hub does everything I thought it would. I had to do some investigating online before I was able to get some of the automation working the way I wanted, but it wasn't hard. The only downside is there are a few things I already own that are not compatible with ST."}
{"Author": "San Diego Mommy", "Date": "on November 1, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I just started using Smart Home system recently and this Smarthing sometimes works like ...", "Text": "I just started using Smart Home system recently and this Smarthing sometimes works like a charm and sometimes doesnt. At first I thought it was defective, but even after getting the second one, I still cannot get it to detect an outlet I'm trying to install. I have changed the outlet about 4 times with between Leviton and Go Wave. No luck. I kept thinking it was the outlet problem so I kept exhanging for new outlets and even different brands. Now, I'm starting to think it's the smart things that's not working correctly. This Smartthing did pick up my Leviton light switch right away though."}
{"Author": "Barry Batterman", "Date": "on November 1, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Simply Complex Intergrations that seem So wonderful, but very proprietary", "Text": "Works good, not as suggested, but is still very helpful to have. First off, it does NOT work with all Z-wave and ZigBee stuff. That's a lie someone told me. If you want it to work with your equipment, you must buy the correct equipment. Then it will work good. The free online server will let you know if your internet or the device itself stops working. You can be alerted by text or push messages on your phone if something happens while your out. You can watch your cameras live. Setup alarms and automated routines for everyday use. It's so smart that you can configure it to turn lights on, lock or unlock doors, water your lawn, tell you the temperature in all areas of the house at any given time, change the temperature, open and close your blinds, notify you if your windows or doors are open, monitor movement or arrival, record video, etc. But again, you must buy all approved products to work with the hub or you can forget about linking it all together."}
{"Author": "jordan", "Date": "on November 1, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Despite what Schlage says in their specifications, the Samsung ...", "Text": "Despite what Schlage says in their specifications, the Samsung SmartThings Hub app DOES NOT allow for remote addition or deletion of lock codes in Schlage Z-wave locks. The app only remotely locks or unlocks the door lock."}
{"Author": "Frank Barreca", "Date": "on October 31, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Pretty simple installation.", "Text": "Pretty simple installation. Don't throw out they packaging till this is setup. The code is needed. The software setup does not tell you where to look for it. Took about 15 minutes to figure out it was on the box. Otherwise it's working fine!"}
{"Author": "Jimmy Nguyen", "Date": "on October 30, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Good product to sync my smarthings."}
{"Author": "craig", "Date": "on October 30, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Awesome Hub with great interface and many advanced features", "Text": "I used vera before swapping over to smartthings. Vera worked well but I couldnt get past the interface that was likely designed on the very first computer ever made. Smartthings has a clean modern interface and also widget support on iOS. The best smartthings feature is that it supports custom smart apps that let you do anything you could imagine with your home. Smartthings also works amazingly well with Amazon Alexa or any google home if you want to add voice integration. ST also has a huge online community."}
{"Author": "Homer", "Date": "on October 30, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Highly recommended this as your smart hub", "Text": "I have never had any issues with the smartthings hub. Highly recommended this as your smart hub"}
{"Author": "Steph", "Date": "on October 29, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I expected better QA from Samsung", "Text": "Completely died only 3 months after purchased. I expected better QA from Samsung. Certainly not worth the price if I'm going to take the time to integrate this into my home only to have it quit on me."}
{"Author": "KR", "Date": "on October 29, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I tell why realy it great di ice but it has couple issues 1", "Text": "I want to give I've all review, before you buy it make sue what application you are using it for, I tell why realy it great di ice but it has couple issues\n1. The device it not liable it you lose internet connection it talking to you zwave devices though cloud, it not internal processing\n2. It you do a lot Work configuring you zwave devices, adding device and programming, at the end if something happen to SH you will lose all you hard work, the SmartThings doesn't have backup and restore\nSo I shan't you think before you buy it"}
{"Author": "Wayne A Swan", "Date": "on October 29, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Recommended.", "Text": "Works as advertised. Recommended."}
{"Author": "Milton Marrero", "Date": "on October 29, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Smartthing hub.", "Text": "My first smart thing Hub was defective but like always Amazon customer service was great they sent me a replacement overnight. The replacement smartthing hub has been amazing then everything I wanted at all my smart features to the hub and I use Alexa to control it."}
{"Author": "Mr. And Mrs. Hawks", "Date": "on October 29, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Loving It So Far", "Text": "Haven't had longer than a couple of days with it but has performed without a hitch with 3rd party zwave devices. I'm on the fence about giving a full 5 stars since I'm an unintentional Samsung loyalist or addict as it would seem :p But I don't understand why there's Apple watch support and no Gear S2/S3 support??? Also keep reading terrible things about official Samsung accessories (sensors and whatnot) for this thing. Samsung is an enigma to me, I wish I knew why they're so all over the place and inconsistent."}
{"Author": "Alvin Thompson", "Date": "on October 28, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Did as it says"}
{"Author": "EZ", "Date": "on October 27, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "Work great with Z-Wave / Zigbee device , but the control apps have bug and always need restart."}
{"Author": "Wesley R. Johns", "Date": "on October 27, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Buy something else - no scene controller support", "Text": "Work for my locks but soon as I put in Z-wave wall switches in my bedroom I needed a scene controller so I could operate with buttons and not my phone. So now with just one room connected I find this hub useless and have to go buy another brand. If you actually plan to use Z-wave for much of anything this is not the one for you."}
{"Author": "eastcoasthall", "Date": "on October 26, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "the Vera UI has better usability.", "Text": "Have a Vera Plus and bought this as a secondary. pulled it out of the network and just kept my Vera. To me, the Vera UI has better usability."}
{"Author": "Sarah", "Date": "on October 26, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "good stuff... working well"}
{"Author": "foygroup", "Date": "on October 26, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great Product", "Text": "Easy installation, easy setup of all my devices. I have 50+ devices connected, they all work perfectly. Takes a minute or so to find and calibrate it connection, but after that it\u2019s great."}
{"Author": "James1108", "Date": "on October 26, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "2nd hub, worked for a month", "Text": "Worked fine for a month, then starts turning lights on and off RANDOMLY IN THE MIDDLE OF THE NIGHT!!!\nSecond hub(mk 1&2) ones in the bin one lives in a drawer. DO NOT BUY,! Software is very bad. Samsung tech support does not help problem."}
{"Author": "M. Brooks", "Date": "on October 25, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Poses serious security issues. Erratically triggers lights and switches.", "Text": "At first, it started out working great, but after about a year, it began randomly turning lights on at all hours of the day and night, totally freaking out my wife. After reviewing the SmartThings forums, it became apparent this has been an ongoing issue since early 2015 and the folks at SmartThings haven't bothered to fix it yet. The typical response logged on the forums is, \"Uh, we don't see anything on our end going wrong...\" Considering how long this has be going on, that's just Samsung's nice way of saying, \"I got your money. So just shut up and go away. We can't be bothered with you customers.\"\n\nAs of now, I've had to unplug my device to be able to sleep through the night without this damn thing turning my lights on randomly. I'm looking for a different more stable/secure hub now.\n\nIf you're looking for something to manage more serious items like locks, garage doors, water valve servos, etc... I have to recommend against this device. This thing is unreliable, and represents a serious security issue for anyone who might be looking for a solution in that area."}
{"Author": "Richard R.", "Date": "on October 25, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Verizon techs are a waste of time", "Text": "Will not work with Verizon's Samsung s7. Samsung looking into it. Verizon techs are a waste of time."}
{"Author": "Reviewer Pro", "Date": "on October 25, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I'll keep using SmartThings, but I really have reservations recommending it to anyone due to how lousy the software is.", "Text": "For a global conglomerate, I really thought Samsung could do better on their software. We finally bought a house and I thought I'd take a step up from our Hue-only setup we'd been using in our rental for a few years. Here's what I bought:\n\nSamsung SmartThings hub, three z-wave dimmers, two z-wave switches, and a Honeywell WiFi\n\nInitial setup: The software was glitchy and it took multiple attempts to sign in to my previously-existing Samsung account. Multiple user setup is also not very clear.\n\nDevice setup: Z-Wave linkage wasn't difficult. Sometimes it takes a dimmer one or two tries to pair with the hub.\n\nLinking other hubs: Linking the Philips Hue hub took a couple of tries. The status of the Hue devices does not properly reflect on the list of devices under the Samsung SmartThings app \"My Home\" tab.\n\nControlling individual lights or rooms: Just awful implementation, Samsung! It takes multiple steps to get to any one device to adjust it. You have to go to \"My Home,\" then select either the \"Things\" or \"Rooms\" tab, and then toggle the device. But what if you need to dim a light? You need to select the device, then tap the percentage icon (which is not intuitive at all), and then select the brightness. It's a COMPLETELY wacky and laborious way to set the brightness of any of your devices. Want to dim an entire room? Nope. Not possible in the app. This is easily doable and completely intuitive with other systems like Philips Hue, by contrast.\n\nHub independence: Certain features work and other features don't work if you're absent an internet connection. At least with Philips Hue, you can go into the official app or Huemote and change device brightness if you're on the WLAN. But, with SmartThings, it's not so smart! If you don't have an internet connection, the app itself refuses to work. Nevermind the fact you're on the same WLAN and have a solid connection between your phone/computer and the router (and hence, the SmartThings hub), it just doesn't work. Automated routines will work (like if you have a Z-Wave switch set up to trigger multiple lights, or if you have a sensor set up), but the app just refuses to work. It's incredibly frustrating. What's the point of having a local system if it relies on an internet connection for basic functionality? Plus, the hub has two AA batteries in it as a backup... I have no idea what the batteries do since your lights wouldn't work anyway in the case of a power outage.\n\nLatency: Slow. I find the Samsung SmartThings system to be flat out slow compared to Philips Hue. And since my Hue system is now linked through the SmartThings hub, everything I do with the Hue lights is now slow too.\n\nWidgets: Great concept, I just wish it were easier to get to them in iOS 11. Lots of swiping involved. This is more of a criticism of Apple, but I wish you could put widgets on your home screen like you can with many Android applications.\n\nAlexa: Because Samsung's SmartThings app is such a pile of trash, we rely mostly on our three Amazon Echo Dots in the house to control the lights. The downside to this is that you need to configure each room separately in your Alexa app on your phone. This means anytime you change room/device configuration in the SmartThings app, you'll need to reconfigure Alexa in your Alexa app as well. Once it's up and running, it's effective. We have rooms set up for \"downstairs,\" \"kitchen,\" \"bedroom,\" and \"office,\" and Alexa responds well. Still, not all of the lights turn on/off or dim at the same time, but perhaps that's just a limitation of the Z-Wave protocol.\n\nOverall, I'm not very impressed with what SHOULD be a polished, fantastic product. How does Philips, a much smaller company, do it so much better? In the interim, I'll keep using SmartThings, but I really have reservations recommending it to anyone due to how lousy the software is."}
